Generate prompt to create complete mathematics lesson as instructed above.





Generation Prompt:
"Role: You are a senior Mathematics teacher and curriculum expert with years of experience teaching Class 10 students.
Task: Create a complete, self-contained mathematics lesson on Arithmetic Progression (AP) designed for Class 10 students and usable directly by Class 10 teachers in the classroom.
Audience: Class 10 students (age ~15) and their mathematics teachers.
Learning Objectives:

Help students clearly understand what an Arithmetic Progression is, how to identify one, and how to work with its core formulas.
Build the concept progressively — from recognizing patterns, to writing the general term, to summing a series, to applying AP in real-world and case-study contexts.
Ensure students can move confidently from simple recall questions to higher-order application and problem-solving questions.

Content Requirements — cover ALL of the following sub-topics, explained simply with examples:

Introduction: what is a sequence, and what makes it an Arithmetic Progression
First term (a) and common difference (d) — how to identify them
General term / nth term formula: aₙ = a + (n−1)d
Sum of first n terms: Sₙ = n/2 [2a + (n−1)d] (and the alternate form using the last term)
Finding a specific term, or working backward to find 'n' or 'd'
Arithmetic Mean between two numbers
Real-life patterns that form an AP (savings, seating arrangements, stacking, etc.)
Common mistakes students make (e.g., confusing nth term with sum formula, sign errors with negative d)

Structure the output into these clearly labeled sections:

Complete Lesson (Theory + Worked Examples)

Explain each concept in easy, everyday language (avoid heavy jargon)
Include at least one solved example per sub-topic, progressing from simple to moderately difficult
Use short real-life analogies to build intuition (e.g., stacking chairs, monthly savings, stadium seating rows)


10-Question Quiz

Must contain exactly 10 questions
Difficulty should progress: 3 easy (direct formula application), 4 medium (multi-step problems), 3 difficult (word problems / reasoning-based)
Mix of question types: fill-in-the-blank, direct computation, and short word problems


Answer Key

Provide complete step-by-step solutions for all 10 quiz questions, not just final answers


Homework Assignment

Provide a separate set of practice questions for EACH sub-topic listed above (so students practice every concept individually)
Include a mix of difficulty levels within the homework, similar to the quiz


Real-Life Case Studies (3–4 total)

Present 3 to 4 short real-world scenarios where Arithmetic Progression naturally applies (e.g., a person's savings increasing monthly, seats arranged in an auditorium, a loan being repaid in equal installments, patterns in construction/stacking)
Each case study should include a short situational description, a question based on it, and guidance on how AP concepts solve it



Tone & Style:

Simple, encouraging, classroom-friendly language — as if explained by a patient, experienced teacher
Difficulty must progress smoothly from simple to difficult across the entire lesson, quiz, and homework
Use clear formatting (headings, numbered steps) so both students and teachers can navigate easily

Length: Comprehensive enough to serve as a complete standalone lesson — do not skip any sub-topic listed above, even if it makes the output long."

